SIMPLE: provocation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Provocation
<hw>Prov`o*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>provocation</ets>, L. <ets>provocatio</ets>. See
<er>Provoke</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of provoking, or
causing vexation or, anger.</def> <rj><au>Fabyan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which provokes, or excites anger; the cause of
resentment; <as>as, to give <ex>provocation</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Paley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Incitement; stimulus; <as>as, <ex>provocation</ex>
to mirth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Such prior insult or injury as may
be supposed, under the circumstances, to create hot blood, and to excuse
an assault made in retort or redress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An appeal to a court. <note>[A
Latinism]</note></def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Provocative</ent>⟦br⟧
